---
import BookLayout from '@layouts/BookLayout.astro';
---

<BookLayout
  title="About"
  description="What the Field Guide for WooCommerce is, who it's for, and how to use it — including for agencies handing off to clients."
  pageClass="is-about"
>
  <article class="about prose">
    <header class="about-header">
      <p class="eyebrow">About</p>
      <h1>What this is</h1>
    </header>

    <p class="lede">
      The Field Guide for WooCommerce is an open, community-maintained
      operational playbook — the book that should ship with WooCommerce but
      doesn't.
    </p>

    <p>
      It covers what you actually run into when you run a store: every product
      type and how it handles inventory; the invisible layer beneath payments;
      the specifics of tax in the US and the EU; the protocols for when
      something breaks; and the code-level patterns for when you outgrow
      extensions.
    </p>

    <h2>Who it's for</h2>

    <p>
      Three audiences, same pages. The lede of each section is plain English —
      written so a merchant new to WooCommerce can follow along. Deeper
      mechanics and code appear under <em>For developers</em> later in the same
      section, so agency builders and developers get what they need too.
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Merchants</strong> running their own Woo store — especially
        when you've hit a wall and the official docs don't answer the
        question.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Agencies and builders</strong> shipping client sites —
        pre-launch checklists, staging pitfalls, handoff practices.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Developers</strong> extending WooCommerce with custom code —
        hook patterns, REST API, HPOS-safe queries.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>How to read it</h2>

    <p>
      Browse the full index, or start with the first section of each part (see
      the homepage). Every section stands alone — you don't have to read in
      order. Search covers the whole book.
    </p>

    <h2>For agencies handing off to clients</h2>

    <p>
      The whole guide is licensed under
      <a href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/" rel="external">
        Creative Commons Attribution 4.0</a
      >. That means you can fork it, rewrite sections in your own voice, strip
      it down to the ten things your client actually needs, and hand it off —
      as long as you credit the source.
    </p>

    <p>
      The whole book is plain Markdown in a public
      <a
        href="https://github.com/namiokuzono/fieldguide-for-woocommerce"
        rel="external">GitHub repo</a
      >. Clone it, edit in your editor of choice, build a client-branded
      version. Every page also has a "Print" button for a quick PDF handoff.
    </p>

    <h2>How it's maintained</h2>

    <p>
      It's a living document. Open an issue or a pull request on GitHub —
      corrections, new sections, better examples are all welcome. See the
      <a
        href="https://github.com/namiokuzono/fieldguide-for-woocommerce/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md"
        rel="external">contributing guide</a
      > for the style.
    </p>
  </article>
</BookLayout>
